<!--
========================================================================
FILE: Home.view.xml — Landing Page / Category Browser
NAMESPACE: com.shopeasy.app.view
========================================================================

[BEGINNER] WHAT IS THIS VIEW?
This is the first page users see when they open ShopEasy. It:
  1. Welcomes the user with a branded header section
  2. Shows product categories fetched from the OData backend
  3. Lets users click a category to browse its products

[INTERMEDIATE] DATA FLOW IN THIS VIEW
  - Page title:       Bound to i18n model → {i18n>homeTitle}
  - Welcome text:     Bound to i18n model → static translated text
  - Categories:       Bound to OData model → {/Categories} entity set
  - Category details: Bound to individual category properties
  - Navigation:       Press event → controller handler → Router.navTo()

Learn more: docs/02-views-and-controllers.md, docs/03-data-binding.md
========================================================================
-->

<mvc:View
    controllerName="com.shopeasy.app.controller.Home"
    xmlns="sap.m"
    xmlns:mvc="sap.ui.core.mvc"
    xmlns:core="sap.ui.core"
    xmlns:l="sap.ui.layout"
    xmlns:f="sap.f"
    xmlns:cssgrid="sap.ui.layout.cssgrid"
>
    <!--
    [BEGINNER] THE <Page> CONTROL
    ====================================================
    sap.m.Page is the fundamental layout control for a single screen.
    It provides:
      - A header bar (with title, nav button, and action buttons)
      - A scrollable content area (where your controls go)
      - An optional footer bar (for bottom actions)

    Think of it like a mobile screen with a top bar and content below.

    title="{i18n>homeTitle}"
      [BEGINNER] DATA BINDING TO i18n MODEL
      The curly braces {} create a DATA BINDING. This tells UI5:
        "Don't use a hardcoded string — get the value from a model."

      Breaking down {i18n>homeTitle}:
        - i18n   → The model NAME (declared in manifest.json)
        - >      → Separator between model name and property path
        - homeTitle → The KEY in the i18n.properties file

      UI5 looks up "homeTitle" in i18n.properties and finds:
        homeTitle=Welcome to ShopEasy
      And displays that as the page title.

      [BEST PRACTICE] ALWAYS use i18n bindings for user-visible text.
      Never hardcode strings like title="Welcome to ShopEasy".
      Reason: If your app needs to support German users, you just
      create i18n_de.properties with the translated keys — no code changes!

    [INTERMEDIATE] PAGE HEADER CUSTOMIZATION
    The Page control automatically creates a sap.m.Bar as its header.
    You can customize it with:
      - showNavButton="true"  → Shows a back arrow (for sub-pages)
      - headerContent         → Aggregation for custom header controls
      - subHeader             → A second bar below the header
    Since Home is the landing page, we don't show a nav button.
    -->
    <Page
        id="homePage"
        title="{i18n>homeTitle}"
    >
        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <VBox> CONTROL — Vertical Layout
        ====================================================
        sap.m.VBox arranges its children vertically (stacked top to bottom).
        It's the UI5 equivalent of CSS flexbox with flex-direction: column.

        Common layout controls in UI5:
          VBox  → Vertical stack (column)
          HBox  → Horizontal stack (row)
          FlexBox → Full flexbox control with all flex properties

        class="sapUiMediumMargin"
          [BEGINNER] SAP CSS MARGIN/PADDING CLASSES
          UI5 provides pre-defined CSS utility classes for spacing:
            sapUiTinyMargin     → 0.5rem margin on all sides
            sapUiSmallMargin    → 1rem margin
            sapUiMediumMargin   → 2rem margin
            sapUiLargeMargin    → 3rem margin

          These also have directional variants:
            sapUiMediumMarginTop, sapUiMediumMarginBottom, etc.
            sapUiSmallMarginBegin, sapUiSmallMarginEnd (RTL-aware!)

          [BEST PRACTICE] Use sapUiMargin* classes instead of custom CSS.
          They respect the current theme and RTL (right-to-left) mode.
          "Begin" and "End" are used instead of "Left" and "Right" to
          support RTL languages like Arabic and Hebrew automatically.
        -->
        <VBox class="sapUiMediumMargin">
            <!--
            [BEGINNER] THE <Title> CONTROL
            sap.m.Title renders a styled heading text. The "level" attribute
            controls the semantic HTML heading level (H1, H2, H3...) for
            accessibility. Screen readers use heading levels to help
            visually impaired users navigate the page structure.

            titleStyle="H1" controls the VISUAL size of the heading.
            level="H1" controls the SEMANTIC meaning for accessibility.

            [BEST PRACTICE] Always set both titleStyle AND level:
              - titleStyle = how it LOOKS (visual)
              - level = what it MEANS (semantic/accessibility)
            They can differ: you might want something that LOOKS like H2
            but IS semantically H1 (the main heading of the page).
            -->
            <Title
                text="{i18n>homeTitle}"
                titleStyle="H1"
                level="H1"
                class="sapUiSmallMarginBottom"
            />

            <!--
            [BEGINNER] THE <Text> CONTROL
            sap.m.Text renders a plain text paragraph. Unlike Title, it
            has no heading semantics — it's just body text.

            Properties:
              text   → The text content (can be bound to a model)
              width  → CSS width (optional, defaults to auto)

            [INTERMEDIATE] Text wrapping behavior:
              - By default, Text wraps to multiple lines
              - Set maxLines="2" to truncate with ellipsis after 2 lines
              - Set wrapping="false" to disable wrapping entirely
            -->
            <Text
                text="{i18n>homeSubtitle}"
                class="sapUiSmallMarginBottom sapThemeText"
            />
        </VBox>

        <!--
        [BEGINNER] THE <IconTabBar> CONTROL — Tab Navigation
        ====================================================
        sap.m.IconTabBar provides a tabbed interface. Each tab can have:
          - An icon
          - A text label
          - A count badge
          - Content below the tab strip

        We're using it here NOT as traditional tabs, but as a visual
        category selector. Users see category icons and click to browse.

        [INTERMEDIATE] IconTabBar has two usage patterns:
          1. TAB CONTAINER: Each tab has different content below it
             (like browser tabs). Use the <items> aggregation with
             <content> inside each IconTabFilter.
          2. FILTER BAR: Tabs act as filters/navigation triggers.
             Pair with a select event handler. Content stays the same
             but the data changes.

        We use pattern #2: clicking a tab navigates to the product list.

        select=".onCategorySelect"
          [BEGINNER] EVENT HANDLING IN XML VIEWS
          The dot-prefix "." means "call a method on the controller".
          So .onCategorySelect calls:
            this.onCategorySelect(oEvent) in Home.controller.js

          [GOTCHA] Without the dot, UI5 looks for a GLOBAL function,
          which almost always fails. Always use the dot prefix!

        headerMode="Inline"
          [INTERMEDIATE] Controls how the tab headers are rendered:
            - "Standard": Icon above text (larger tabs)
            - "Inline": Icon and text side by side (compact tabs)

        class="sapUiResponsiveContentPadding"
          [INTERMEDIATE] A responsive padding class that adjusts padding
          based on screen size. On phones it's small, on desktops it's larger.
          This is part of UI5's responsive design system.
        -->
        <IconTabBar
            id="categoryTabBar"
            select=".onCategorySelect"
            headerMode="Inline"
            class="sapUiResponsiveContentPadding"
            stretchContentHeight="false"
            expandable="false"
        >
            <!--
            [BEGINNER] THE <items> AGGREGATION
            ====================================================
            In UI5, a control can contain other controls through
            "aggregations". The <items> element is the aggregation of
            IconTabBar that holds its tab items (IconTabFilter controls).

            [BEGINNER] AGGREGATION BINDING — Repeating a Template
            Instead of manually writing one <IconTabFilter> per category,
            we use AGGREGATION BINDING to automatically create one for
            EACH entry in the /Categories entity set.

            items="{/Categories}"
              This tells UI5:
                1. Read the /Categories collection from the default model
                2. For each category in the collection, create ONE
                   IconTabFilter using the template below
                3. Each generated IconTabFilter gets a "binding context"
                   pointing to its category data

              It's similar to React's:
                {categories.map(cat => <Tab key={cat.id} .../>)}

            [INTERMEDIATE] BINDING SYNTAX BREAKDOWN
              items="{/Categories}"
                - { }          → Data binding expression
                - /            → Root of the model (absolute path)
                - Categories   → The OData entity set name

              This is the SHORT syntax for aggregation binding. The full
              (complex) syntax allows more options:
                items="{
                  path: '/Categories',
                  sorter: { path: 'Name', descending: false },
                  filters: [{ path: 'Active', operator: 'EQ', value1: true }]
                }"

            [ADVANCED] OData AGGREGATION BINDING INTERNALS
            When UI5 processes items="{/Categories}":
              1. It creates an ODataListBinding for path "/Categories"
              2. The ODataModel sends: GET /sap/opu/odata/sap/SHOP_SRV/Categories
              3. The response contains an array of category entities
              4. For each entity, UI5 clones the template (IconTabFilter)
              5. Each clone gets a binding context like "/Categories('CAT001')"
              6. Property bindings inside the template (like {Name}) resolve
                 relative to this context
            -->
            <items>
                <!--
                [BEGINNER] THE <IconTabFilter> CONTROL — A Single Tab
                ====================================================
                Each IconTabFilter represents one tab in the IconTabBar.

                key="{CategoryId}"
                  A unique identifier for this tab. Used in the select
                  event to know WHICH category the user clicked.
                  Bound to the CategoryId property of each category entity.

                text="{Name}"
                  The label displayed on the tab. Bound to the category Name.
                  Example: "Electronics", "Clothing", "Books"

                icon="{Icon}"
                  An icon displayed on the tab. UI5 uses the SAP icon font.
                  Example: "sap-icon://laptop" shows a laptop icon.
                  Browse all icons: https://sapui5.hana.ondemand.com/test-resources/sap/m/demokit/iconExplorer/webapp/index.html

                count="{__count}"
                  [INTERMEDIATE] Shows a badge number on the tab.
                  The __count property comes from $inlinecount in OData
                  or can be a property on the category entity itself.
                  This shows how many products are in each category.

                [BEGINNER] RELATIVE vs ABSOLUTE BINDING PATHS
                Notice we use {Name} not {/Name}. The leading slash
                matters enormously:
                  {/Name}  → ABSOLUTE path: looks at root of the model
                  {Name}   → RELATIVE path: relative to the binding context

                Since this IconTabFilter is inside an aggregation bound
                to {/Categories}, each instance gets a context like
                "/Categories('CAT001')". The relative path {Name} resolves
                to "/Categories('CAT001')/Name".

                Think of it like file paths:
                  /users/john/name  → absolute (from root)
                  name              → relative (from current directory)
                -->
                <IconTabFilter
                    key="{CategoryId}"
                    text="{Name}"
                    icon="{Icon}"
                    count="{ProductCount}"
                />
            </items>

            <!--
            [INTERMEDIATE] THE <content> AGGREGATION
            ====================================================
            The content below the tab strip. This area shows details
            about the selected category and a prompt to browse products.
            -->
            <content>
                <VBox
                    class="sapUiSmallMargin"
                    alignItems="Center"
                >
                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] THE <IllustratedMessage> CONTROL
                    ====================================================
                    sap.m.IllustratedMessage shows a graphical illustration
                    with a title and description. UI5 comes with built-in
                    illustration types for common scenarios:
                      - EmptyList
                      - NoSearchResults
                      - NoData
                      - ErrorScreen
                      - SuccessScreen
                      and many more...

                    illustrationType="sapIllus-SimpleBalloon"
                      Points to a built-in illustration SVG. SAP provides
                      a library of professional illustrations that match
                      the Fiori design language.

                    [BEST PRACTICE] Use IllustratedMessage for empty states
                    and error states instead of just showing blank space.
                    Good UX always tells the user WHY something is empty
                    and WHAT they can do about it.
                    -->
                    <IllustratedMessage
                        illustrationType="sapIllus-SimpleBalloon"
                        title="{i18n>homeTitle}"
                        description="{i18n>homeSubtitle}"
                    >
                        <!--
                        [BEGINNER] additionalContent AGGREGATION
                        IllustratedMessage has a special aggregation for
                        adding interactive controls (buttons, links) below
                        the illustration and text.
                        -->
                        <additionalContent>
                            <!--
                            [BEGINNER] THE <Button> CONTROL
                            ====================================================
                            sap.m.Button is the most fundamental interactive control.

                            text="{i18n>continueShopping}"
                              Button label from i18n.

                            type="Emphasized"
                              [BEGINNER] Button types control visual styling:
                                - "Default"    → Standard grey button
                                - "Emphasized" → Primary action (blue/highlighted)
                                - "Accept"     → Positive action (green tint)
                                - "Reject"     → Negative action (red tint)
                                - "Transparent" → No background (text-only look)
                                - "Ghost"      → Transparent with border on hover

                              [BEST PRACTICE] Only ONE button per page should be
                              "Emphasized" — the primary action the user should take.
                              Having multiple emphasized buttons confuses users.

                            press=".onContinueShopping"
                              [BEGINNER] The press event fires when the user clicks
                              or taps the button. The "." prefix calls the method
                              on the controller.
                            -->
                            <Button
                                text="{i18n>continueShopping}"
                                type="Emphasized"
                                press=".onCategorySelect"
                            />
                        </additionalContent>
                    </IllustratedMessage>
                </VBox>
            </content>
        </IconTabBar>

        <!--
        [INTERMEDIATE] GRID LIST FOR CATEGORY CARDS
        ====================================================
        Below the IconTabBar, we also show categories as visual cards
        in a responsive grid layout. This provides an alternative
        browsing experience.

        [ADVANCED] THE <f:GridList> CONTROL
        sap.f.GridList is a list control that arranges its items in a
        CSS Grid layout. Unlike a regular List that stacks items
        vertically, GridList can create multi-column card layouts.

        The f: prefix maps to the sap.f library (Fiori controls),
        declared in the xmlns:f attribute on the View element.
        -->
        <f:GridList
            id="categoryGrid"
            headerText="{i18n>category}"
            items="{/Categories}"
            class="sapUiSmallMargin"
        >
            <!--
            [ADVANCED] CUSTOM GRID LAYOUT
            ====================================================
            The customLayout aggregation lets you define the CSS Grid
            template for the GridList. GridBoxLayout provides a
            simplified API for common grid patterns.

            boxMinWidth="16rem"
              Each card is at least 16rem wide. The grid automatically
              calculates how many columns fit in the available space:
                - 320px viewport → 1 column
                - 768px viewport → 2-3 columns
                - 1200px viewport → 4+ columns

            [INTERMEDIATE] This is pure CSS Grid under the hood.
            UI5 generates: grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fill, minmax(16rem, 1fr))
            This is a modern responsive pattern that adapts without
            media queries — the grid itself decides column count.
            -->
            <f:customLayout>
                <cssgrid:GridBoxLayout boxMinWidth="16rem" />
            </f:customLayout>

            <!--
            [INTERMEDIATE] GridListItem — Each Category Card
            ====================================================
            sap.f.GridListItem is a list item designed for grid layouts.

            type="Active"
              [BEGINNER] List item types control interactivity:
                - "Inactive"    → No press effect, not clickable
                - "Active"      → Highlights on press, fires press event
                - "Navigation"  → Shows a chevron (>) indicating navigation
                - "Detail"      → Shows a detail button
                - "DetailAndActive" → Both detail button and press

              We use "Active" so the card highlights when tapped, giving
              the user visual feedback that it's interactive.

            press=".onCategoryPress"
              Fires when the user clicks/taps this card. The controller
              handler reads the CategoryId from the binding context and
              navigates to the productList route.

            [INTERMEDIATE] EXPRESSION BINDING EXAMPLE
            ====================================================
            Expression binding allows inline JavaScript expressions in
            XML views. The syntax is: {= expression }

            Example used below on the VBox:
              visible="{= ${ProductCount} > 0 }"

            Breaking it down:
              {= ... }           → Expression binding delimiters
              ${NumberOfProducts} → Read the NumberOfProducts property
                                    ($ is required inside expressions)
              > 0                → JavaScript comparison

            This evaluates to true/false, controlling visibility.
            Only categories with products are shown.

            [ADVANCED] EXPRESSION BINDING CAPABILITIES
            Expression binding supports:
              - Comparison: ==, !=, <, >, <=, >=
              - Logical: &&, ||, !
              - Ternary: condition ? 'yes' : 'no'
              - Math: +, -, *, /
              - String: + (concatenation)
              - Type cast: ${path} (reads from model)
              - Formatter: Not supported (use regular binding)

            Limitations:
              - No function calls (no .toUpperCase(), etc.)
              - No variable declarations
              - No loops or conditionals (only ternary)
              - Harder to debug than formatters (no breakpoints)

            [BEST PRACTICE] Use expression binding for simple boolean
            checks (visibility, enabled state). Use formatters for
            anything more complex.
            -->
            <f:GridListItem
                type="Active"
                press=".onCategoryPress"
            >
                <VBox
                    class="sapUiSmallMargin"
                    height="8rem"
                >
                    <!--
                    [BEGINNER] <core:Icon> — Displaying Icons
                    ====================================================
                    sap.ui.core.Icon renders an icon from the SAP icon font.

                    src="{Icon}"
                      Bound to the Icon property of the category entity.
                      Values look like: "sap-icon://laptop"

                    size="2rem"
                      The icon size in CSS units.

                    color="#0854A0"
                      The icon color. You can use hex colors or UI5 theme
                      parameters like "Default", "Positive", "Critical".

                    [INTERMEDIATE] SAP ICON FONT
                    UI5 includes 500+ vector icons via a custom web font.
                    They scale perfectly at any size (no pixelation) and
                    can be colored with CSS.

                    All icons use the "sap-icon://" protocol prefix.
                    Browse them: search for "Icon Explorer" in UI5 demo kit.
                    -->
                    <core:Icon
                        src="{Icon}"
                        size="2rem"
                        class="sapUiSmallMarginBottom"
                    />

                    <Title text="{Name}" level="H3" />

                    <!--
                    [INTERMEDIATE] EXPRESSION BINDING FOR DYNAMIC TEXT
                    ====================================================
                    Here we use expression binding to construct a dynamic
                    string that includes a model value:

                    text="{= ${NumberOfProducts} + ' Products'}"

                    This concatenates the NumberOfProducts value with the
                    static string ' Products'. For example:
                      NumberOfProducts = 12 → "12 Products"

                    [BEST PRACTICE] In production, the static text
                    ' Products' should come from i18n for translation.
                    For learning purposes, we inline it here to
                    demonstrate expression binding string concatenation.
                    -->
                    <Text
                        text="{= ${ProductCount} + ' Products'}"
                        class="sapUiTinyMarginTop"
                    />
                </VBox>
            </f:GridListItem>
        </f:GridList>

    </Page>

</mvc:View>
